[1] Malaysia (Negeri Sembilan)
Date: Wed 29 Mar 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Bernama, 29 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.bernama.com.my/bernama/v3/news.php?id=188736>

13 HFMD cases detected in N Sembilan, hospitals on alert
--------------------------------------------------------
13 cases of hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) were detected in Negeri
Sembilan from January 2006 to last Monday [27 Mar 2006?], said state health
director Datuk Dr Rosnah Ismail. She said 9 were detected in Seremban, 3 in
Jempol, and one in Tampin.
The situation was not alarming, unlike in Sarawak, but all hospitals,
medical centers and government clinics statewide had been told to be on
alert, she told Bernama here on Wednesday [29 Mar 2006]. "So far, no child
care centers and kindergartens have been ordered to close, because the
situation is under control," she said. She advised all creches [day care
centers] to ensure the cleanliness of their premises.
The disease is caused by a virus that can be found in children's excrement
and can be infectious, she said. Dr Rosnah also advised the public to
immediately send their children for treatment if they showed symptoms of
HFMD, like having a fever and rashes. As of last Sunday [26 Mar 2006?],
Sarawak recorded 6718 HFMD cases, including 8 deaths, since it was detected
in Sibu last month [February 2006].
--
