[2] Singapore
Date: Wed 29 Mar 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Alertnet, 29 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/SIN30527.htm>

Singapore: hand, foot and mouth cases surge
-------------------------------------------
The number of cases of children with hand, foot and mouth disease in
Singapore more than doubled to 785 last week, up from 372 the week before,
the Straits Times newspaper reported on Wednesday [29 Mar 2006].
Two more child care centers [daycare centers] have been forced to shut down
for 10 days, bringing the number of such closures in the city state to 3,
the paper said.
Singapore has recorded 2180 cases of the disease since the start of the
year [2006]. It mainly affects children under the age of 10, causing fever,
mouth ulcers, and rashes. Though most cases have been mild, the health
ministry has tightened the guidelines for when preschools, kindergartens,
and child care centers should close to prevent transmissions. Child care
centers must now shut their doors if they have had infections for more than
15 days, affecting more than 13 children, or 18 per cent of the student
population, the newspaper said.
More than 4000 children have been infected with the disease in East
Malaysia this year [2006], and 8 have died. There has been one death in
Brunei. According to the World Health Organization, there is no specific
antiviral treatment for enterovirus infections such as the hand, foot and
mouth disease. Treatment focuses on the management of complications.
